Philippines Stocks: Atlas Mining, First Gen, Metropolitan Bank

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-07-15T04:38:33Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-15/ayala-first-philippine-robinsons-philippines-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the noon close in  Manila .  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 0.8 percent to a
record 4,458.74. The gauge added 1.5 percent this week, the
fourth consecutive weekly increase.  Gold producers:  Manila Mining Corp. (MAB) ’s Class B shares (MAB
PM), which have no ownership restrictions, rose 2 percent to
5.20 centavos, the highest close since Sept. 19, 1995. Its Class
A shares (MA PM), which are reserved for Filipinos, gained 2
percent to 5.20 centavos.  Atlas Consolidated Mining &
Development (AT)  Corp increased 1.1 percent to 23.50 pesos.  Gold for immediate delivery climbed to a record $1,594.45
an ounce yesterday. Twenty-four of 27 traders, investors and
analysts surveyed by Bloomberg said bullion will climb next
week.  First Gen Corp. (FGEN)  , a power producer, jumped 2.7
percent to 15.46 pesos, the highest close since April 2008.
Parent  First Philippine Holdings Corp. (FPH)   said it will
subscribe for up to 6 billion pesos worth of First Gen’s
preferred shares. First Philippine rose 0.6 percent to 61.25
pesos, the highest close since June 10.  Metropolitan Bank & Trust (MBT)  Co, the second-largest
Philippine bank by assets, climbed 3.4 percent to 79.55 pesos,
taking a three-day advance to 11 percent. The shares rose to the
highest close since Nov. 5 amid speculation the company will
post the “sharpest” earnings growth among the nation’s major
lenders, according to Daniel Picache, an analyst at DBP-Daiwa SB
Capital Markets  Philippines .  Arthur Ty, Metropolitan Bank’s president, couldn’t
immediately be reached in his office for comment.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
 isayson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
